# Section 5 — Learning Reflection

While implementing the Data Structures Library, my primary focus was ensuring that each data structure worked correctly in isolation. Integrating those same data structures into the crawler project demonstrated that a reusable library requires more than correct algorithms—it also requires interfaces that accommodate real application usage.

The Frontier implementation revealed that accepting only non-const references unnecessarily restricted how objects could be inserted into the Queue. Supporting temporary objects through const references made the interface significantly more flexible without affecting correctness.

The SeenStore implementation reinforced the importance of designing supporting components, such as hashing functions, alongside the primary data structures. Although the HashMap itself had already been implemented, integrating it into a practical application exposed missing dependencies and assumptions that were not apparent during standalone testing.

This implementation phase improved my understanding of designing reusable software components. I learned that integration often exposes interface weaknesses that isolated testing cannot reveal, making application-level development an essential part of validating a library's design.